Question:
If the system of equations  \begin{align*}
3x+y&=a,\\
2x+5y&=2a,
\end{align*} has a solution $(x,y)$ when $x=2$, compute $a$.

Candidate Solution:
We substitute $x = 2$ into the system of equations and simplify the equations:
\begin{align*}
3x+y&=a\\
2x+5y&=2a\\
\end{align*}
\begin{align*}
6+y&=a\\
4+5y&=2a\\
\end{align*}
\begin{align*}
y&=a-6\\
5y&=2a-4\\
\end{align*}
\begin{align*}
2a-6&=a-6\\
2a-4&=5a-30\\
\end{align*}
\begin{align*}
a&=a\\
2a+34&=5a\\
\end{align*}
\begin{align*}
0&=0\\
34&=3a\\
\end{align*}
\begin{align*}
0&=0\\
a&=\frac{34}{3}\\
\end{align*}
So $a=\boxed{34/3}$.


Ground-Truth Final Answer:
\frac{26}{3}


